•  The Supreme Law of the Land  
  In the United States the “supreme Law of the Land” is the U.S. Constitution (Art. VI, cl. 2, the Supremacy Clause). Every other source of law—federal statutes, treaties, state constitutions, state statutes, local ordinances, and administrative rules—must be consistent with the Constitution or it can be struck down by the courts.

•  Statutes  
  Statutes are laws enacted by a legislature (Congress at the federal level, or a state legislature at the state level). They:
     – begin as bills, are passed by both legislative chambers, and are signed (or allowed to become law) by the executive;  
     – are usually compiled in chronological “session laws” and then codified by subject (e.g., the United States Code or a state code);  
     – have general, prospective application and are superior to any conflicting ordinances or administrative rules, but subordinate to the Constitution.

•  Ordinances  
  Ordinances are laws adopted by a subordinate unit of government such as a city, town, county, or other municipal corporation. They:  
     – derive their authority from state enabling acts or a state constitution;  
     – deal with purely local matters (zoning, building codes, noise limits, parking regulations, etc.);  
     – must not conflict with state or federal statutes or the U.S. (or relevant state) Constitution.

•  Administrative Rule (Regulation)  
  An administrative rule—often called a regulation—is a standard adopted by an executive-branch agency acting under statutory authority delegated by the legislature. Such rules:  
     – fill in the details needed to implement and enforce statutes (e.g., EPA emission limits, IRS tax-reporting requirements);  
     – are created through rule-making procedures (notice-and-comment, etc.) required by the Administrative Procedure Act (APA) or its state counterpart;  
     – have the force and effect of law so long as they stay within the scope of the enabling statute and do not conflict with superior law.

Hierarchy (highest to lowest): U.S. Constitution → federal statutes & treaties → state constitutions → state statutes → local ordinances → administrative rules (federal or state) created under statutory authority.
